    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I'm reviewing a procurement agreement and need a clarification on the force majeure provision. The clause states: \"Neither party shall be liable for any failure to perform its obligations hereunder if such failure is caused by an event of Force Majeure, defined as unforeseeable circumstances beyond a party's reasonable control, including but not limited to acts of God, war, or sudden catastrophic failure of regional utility infrastructure.\" \n\nIf a sudden, localized power grid failure occurs due to an unpredicted surge, would that typically qualify as an \"unforeseeable circumstance\" under this specific wording? Please analyze the implications of the \"unforeseeable\" requirement in this context.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
